    "description": {
      "gm": "",
      "value": "<p id=\"docs-internal-guid-aa710e2c-7fff-46b0-5a3f-050ca8b5a0a2\" dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;text-indent:13.5pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Prerequisites </span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">tribe of bones, trained in Religion</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;text-indent:13.5pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">You may sanctify a corpse within reach. If the corpse has an undead already (such as a ghost), you become aware of it. Its location also becomes known if within 100 feet of you. If not, the corpse becomes ash in a sudden conflagration of purple flames. Such ash is useless for all necromantic activities, preventing the previous owner from being raised as undead against their will.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;text-indent:13.5pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Tribe of bones pony necromancers who follow the ancient rites of seeking permission of the departed spirit may use the ash as if it were a fully intact body.</span></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>"
